name: NBN: Market Dominance
description: Operation and ICE economy based NBN deck.

name: Iain's Connections 2.0
description:
I made this a 45 card deck and it has Keyhole, to focus on R&D and Archives very much aside from HQ, and Decoy too, just in case. What do you guys think of this?

Here's the original one: http://netrunnerdb.com/en/decklist/4880/iain-s-connections

name: Andy Flexible Aggression
description:
This is actually my first A:NR deck. I chose Andy for the 9 cards, to get what I need at the start of the game and build from there. The idea is to start running aggressively from the beginning, using your special orders to find the icebreakers you need. Test Run is there as the second copy of either Sneakdoor Beta or Keyhole, whichever you need at the time, plus, it can get you back a breaker if it got trashed somehow.

Hostage is there for the midgame, to get you whatever you are missing. Mr. Li for digging, Kati for money, Professional contacts for card drawing, Fall Guy against trashing and Decoy for the possibility of tags you cant avoid.

Cyberfeeder is there to help with the economy, and I only have one Desperado, so that's why I put 2 Dyson chips.

The few times I've played it has performed well. I can usually get enough runs on R&D or HQ as needed to pressure the corp, but I feel the deck lacks something, like it's missing some omph!, so I'll be glad if you can actually comment and suggest ideas for improving it.

name: Annoying to Perfection
description:
The idea is to go against the usual Jinteki approach and win by scoring agendas. Replicating Perfection makes this posible by forcing the runner to run centrals first. The decks annoys the runner by making everything so expensive that it's impossible to run every turn.

You should put your most taxing ICE on centrals, so that the runner is forced to either pay a lot or get really hurt, so you get scoring windows for your agendas. You're also trying to make the runner poor by making him pay a lot trash your resources (which he can get to only after running centrals).

Now the agendas.Since almost all of your agendas force the runner to pay for them, they need lots of money to run, because they need to pay for your ICE first, and then they need to have enough money to steal your agendas, so you use that time to score before they have enough money to run.

There's a secondary flatline alternative if the runner gets to greedy/unlucky, but it's more to annoy them and take tempo away. Also, shocks protect your archives.

I think there's a lot of room for improvement, but I'm still testing the deck, so any suggestions are appreciated in the comments.

name: Magnum Tenma 1.0 (Looking for feedback)
description:
This is my first try with Tenma.

The idea is to focus on central servers, while having enough tricks to access some remotes when you need it.

MUs should be fine, since I have very few programs and not any combination other than Alias-Breach-Passport-Magnum.

I am not sure about economy, which would probably be weak until I get Magnum Opus.

Looking for comments and feedback!!!!!!!!!!!!

name: Medical Emergency
description:
Jinteki rush deck. Six points to win means that only two 3-point agendas are required to win. This deck is focused on finding them and scoring them as soon as possible.

Caprice Nisei pairs well with this deck. Something that will happen often is placing her in HQ to deter Account Siphons, scoring your first Agenda using ice while the runner does not have the right breakers out yet, and then using a second copy to try to score your second agenda. Or if you're ballsy/desperate, Mushin-No-Shin a new server with an agenda, install caprice, and win the psi-game 4 times in a row (hats off to you if you do)

Overdrawing and discarding with Anonymous Tip is common, but keep in mind that if you toss an agenda and Shi-Kyu into your archives, it basically cancels out because the runner still needs to score another agenda. Assuming that you can trigger the Shi-Kyu, that is.

One copy of AggSec for a nasty surprise, but feel free to replace with JuneBug or some other trap or even a third copy of Blue Level Clearance. I chose AggSec, though, because if it goes off, it usually means I can score my next agenda (usually the win) easily.

name: 1st Attempt at Gabriel (looking for feedback)
description: New to the game, only have Core Set, Trace Amount & Cyber Exodus. Any and all feedback welcome. Thanks.

name: Anarch Denial 12
A Silly Deck
Mind Theory
description:
Hi This decks still in theory stages and is something i am planning to use when Honor & Profit comes out. any suggestions are welcome.

The Idea is to use Overmind early game and use Atman later when you know corps ice strength. The E3 feedback's are to save counters on the Overmind & Scavenge allows you to rest counters on Overmind. Test run allows some free use of Overmind and to go find it. The underworld and rabbits are for a constant flow of cash for no clicks. The ICE carver is an off thought for a round about +1 strength to the Overmind.

name: Armchair v1
Diversified Assets v2
description:
Second version of my Tennin deck. Like the first, this deck works is designed for adaptability but is a little more streamlined. It tries to win through scoring agendas or through damaging the runner.

All agendas do damage or tax money in some manner or do both. ICE is designed to be tricksy, force runners into traps, etc. It's a little pricey, but I tried to keep the burst econ cheap to play but have alot of recurring credits that are high cost for the runner to trash. They also help with diversified assets and just throwing out tons of remote servers to keep the runner guessing.

name: Advanced Weyland: We were just never on the grid.
description: So, I've been playing around with advancing weyland for a while now, and after many decks, I've come to this. This has been more successful than my previous builds, and is generally fun to play. 1-bad pub stacking is awesome with Ireress 2-No scorches because of the lack of tagging 3-Caprice + Off the grid has never made any one happy on an advanced ice HQ 4-Program trashing, Just in-case

name: Silgrift
description:
Untested Silhouette deck, trying to use mostly new cards and cards I don't use too often, instead of the gotos like sneak door and account siphon.

Basic strategy is run on the centrals frequently using run events whenever possible. Use your expose to find out about the ice and more importantly whenever they install something in a remote. Then use running interference plus crypsis to get into the remote only when you know it's an agenda.

name: House of Cards
description:
This deck requires a certain amount of ballsiness to play. All of the ICE crumbles to Parasite. Your income comes only from drip Assets and clicking. There's not a reliable way to flatline the Runner.

Ideally the Runner will find the lone Project Junebug in HQ or R&D and wonder if the card you installed with Mushin no Shin is a second. Hopefully it's a GRNDL Refinery.

I'm still tinkering with the ICE and wondering if there's a place for Susanoo-no-Mikoto or something that tags (it used to run Shadow).

name: Fast Jinteki, Shi Kyu
Fellowship of the Rig
Nobody Likes Your Remote Servers and Nobody Likes Your Face
description: Focus is on core server ice breakers (with Crypsis and Quest Completed to potentially handle remote servers.) I chose Logos over Desperado mostly because it's novel. But, beyond that, it also gives an additional card (defense against Jinteki jerks) and has a Shaper-esque tutoring of cards. Run early and run often on those core servers; this deck likely falls apart in the late game.

name: Fatale Atman
description: This is what i currently run. I originally run parasite's in here but took them out because i could either never find them or make much use out of them the Femme's just let me through so much theirs little point in killing ice i find, combined with scavenge to put them where i need them or test running them to blast through a remote for a turn. Input is welcome :)

name: Tennin Test
Silhouette Stealth Quest
description:
Alias, Breach and Passport to hit centrals. Sneakdoor puts pressure on the corporation to armor archives to minimize Silhouette + blackguards ability combo. Feint +inside job +Quest completed should help out when you know the corporation is putting down and trying to score an agenda.

Motivation + Oracle May help with cycling cards and getting credits. Security testing will also help with getting those precious credits each turn. Sure Gamble there to give a little boost to help get blackguard out.

name: Typical Parasite Express
description: ...Tenma with datasuckers and parasites...Using the influence for more clone-chips. Lacks a good code-gate breaker. The build works fair enough but on the originality side everyone's mom and their dog could manage that much.

name: Kate: Critical Hit v4
description:
EDIT v4 BETA: This deck is a complete overhaul of my original Kate: critical hit deck. I dropped modded, because i almost exclusively used it to bring out my toolbox. I also removed the armitages and one lucky find to put in three Magnum Opus.

The economy engine works really really well and i dont have money problems at all.

Another change i made was to drop chakana and use legwork as a weapon against fast advance instead. To get more versatility i replaced the r&d-interfaces with indexing and added more SoT.

Original Critical Hit-Deck: This deck works as a mixture between fast and big rig. Although you try to establish your rig as fast as possible you are able to run early without worrying too much about traps and destroyers thanks to smc, clone-chip, deus x and sharpshooter. The burst-eco cards and kate's ability in addition should help getting out anything you need as fast as possible (e.g. an early toolbox). Although this deck is more or less able to run often, it is recommended to primarly focus on getting the rig out and make worthy runs.

The clone chips are not only good for getting out a trashed sharpshooter or deus x, they also work great with kate's ability to get a cloak or something cheaper during the corps turn.

Chakana and r&d interface are obviously there for r&d pressure and to slow down fast advance alot. I am still considering to drop chakana for something more worthy though, to keep the pressure on another server as well (hq/archives).

Silencer, cloak and dagger are my cheap tools to defeat almost any sentry. The only thing that can stop this combo is an ice-deep server with lots of high strength sentries in it, but this doesnt happen too often, and if i realize, that this might be the case, i just can use sharpshooter and deus x if needed.

Modded is mainly used for hardware like toolbox and the interfaces.

Levy AR and SoT are my panic buttons, because it sometimes may happen, that i draw through my stack very fast, and with Levy i just can restart and play all my beautiful burst economy cards again.

I am still unsure what to use instead of chakana, so any considerations are highly appreciated.

I only had the chance to playtest the deck a few times, but everything seemed to work quite well and i didn't loose a game until now. Edit: -1 Akamatsu MemChip, because i realized, that zu13 costs zero MU, as soon as toolbox hits the table :)

name: Untrashable v6
description:
The Untrashable for the Honor & Profit era. I can't express how much The Future Perfect helps this deck

This deck is built on the idea that running any single remote against Jinteki:RP is going to be more expensive, and then makes your assets and upgrades even more costly to trash with Encryption Protocols.

Eventually you want a good pile of money plus Ash + Hokusai Combo with some Encryption Protocols on the side. Effectively you would force the runner to have to waste 3 clicks, take 2 damage and spend a good pile of credits just to take a look at a remote once. Then you recur your Ash with Howards or Interns.

Sundew is the star of this deck. Protect it early with a Chimera or leave it unprotected if the runner does not trash assets and it can proivide a truckload of money over the course of the game.

This is a version with less econ (just 6 assets) but with Archives punishment instead. Those in turn function kinda like a soft econ, as you can drop them in archives and discourage sucker/desperado runs without using any ICE. Unfortunately the runner can still run and jackout without accessing, so eventually you'll prolly want something light as well there, like a shadow.

Because shocks and shi.kyu discourage Archives access, very often you'll be able to hide one or two agendas in there for a longer time than usual, giving you a breather.

Closed Accounts might seem like a weird card in this deck, but it has caught a lot of players unaware, especially if they gathered a few tags from shadows before this hit the table. However it's there primarily for counter to tag-me/siphon runners, because otherwise they will walk all over you.

name: Monolithic Studios
description: Draw a bunch of cards and get your monolith out, perhaps with the help of the personal workshop plus stimhack combo. Then run R&D a lot and force them to wipe chakana counters every few turns. Atman can deal with archer who is too expensive to pass with creeper. Don't worry about being too fancy with SMC, just grab your early magnum opus if you need it.
